message:
if by niche internet initiatives you mean, the most important work on planet earth:

> the infrastructure of self-awareness for something much bigger than any of us

😄

So how does it work? The core insight is, unlike every other database that exists, you don't store state directly. Instead, you create and index changes over time. Each change has the same schema - the entire database exists with a single schema for every record. That schema represents a *delta*, and it looks something like this.

Imagine that you want to capture the idea that some person works for some company. Rather than adding a record to an Employees table, you'd create a delta that asserts that this relationship came to exist as of some point in time.

```
{
  id: // some long unique key, like a UUID
  timestamp: // the timestamp at which this delta was created
  creator: // the UUID of the entity that created this delta. This could be a user or a function or whatever.
  host: // an identifier for the specific database instance where this delta was created. Either a UUID or a URL, we can figure out the best approach
  pointers: [
    { 
      name: "employee", 
      target: // UUID of the person who has started this job
      backpointer: "employer" // from the perspective of this target, what property is this associated with?
    },
    {
      name: "employer",
      target: // UUID of the company that has employed this person
      backpointer: "employees" // from the perspective of this target, what property is this associated with?
    }
  ]
}
```

This is a fairly simple example, but the idea is that this delta captures a set of invariants that are all either true or false together. Once created, a delta is immutable - if this person quits this job, you don't mutate this delta and you don't erase it. Rather, you create a new delta that targets *this delta* under a negation pointer.

This has all sorts of really powerful implications. For starters, do you see how this sets up a situation where if you have a bunch of deltas all pointing at our hypothetical person, it becomes really easy to use the backpointers to generate an object representing that person? Let's say we have a few more deltas:

```
{
  id,
  timestamp,
  creator,
  host,
  pointers: [
    { 
      name: "person", 
      target: // UUID of our person
      backpointer: "name"
    },
    {
      name: "name",
      target: "John Doe" // rather than a UUID, this is just a raw primitive string
      // note that there's no backpointer here. We could have one, but with primitives we often leave them out. More below.
    }
  ]
}
```

```
{
  id
  timestamp 
  creator
  host
  pointers: [
    { 
      name: "person", 
      target: // UUID of John Doe
      backpointer: "birthday" // from the perspective of this target, what property is this associated with?
    },
    {
      name: "birthday",
      target: // ISO timestamp for someone's date of birth
    }
  ]
}
```

We now have deltas setting a name, birthday and employer on the entity with that UUID. That means we can embed these deltas under their backpointers into a lossless representation of this person:

```
{
  id // the UUID of this individual
  name: [
    // just directly embed the delta that specified this person's name
  ],
  birthday: [
    // directly embed the delta that specified birthday
  ],
  employer: [
    // directly embed the employment delta
  ]
}
```

